441107305581 de Blasio, Bill SYND CODES_REVIEWED Wires NY Politics </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">NYPO </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">US</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Chirlane McCray's Job Approval Higher Among New York's Black Voters; The wife of Mayor Bill de Blasio faces a similar racial gap as her husband, a new poll finds</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>A longstanding racial gap over how New York City voters view Mayor Bill de Blasio appears to extend to his wife, Chirlane McCray, a new poll suggests.</Para><Para>A Quinnipiac University poll Wednesday found that 57% of black voters approve of the job Ms. McCray is doing as first lady, compared with 39% of white voters. Among Hispanic voters, 47% approved.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The first lady's overall approval rating is 43%, while 28% of respondents don't approve of the job she is doing.</Para><Para>The poll comes weeks after Ms. McCray <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wife-of-new-york-mayor-is-considering-running-for-office-1520971385?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=4">said she is considering running for elected office</ELink>, likely in 2021, when Mr. de Blasio's term is up.</Para><Para>For years, black New York City voters have been overwhelmingly more supportive of the Democratic mayor than their white counterparts.</Para><Para>Ms. McCray has taken an increasingly high-profile role in her husband's administration. She leads the city's more than $800 million mental-health initiative, known as Thrive NYC, as well as the city's nonprofit, the Mayor's Fund to Advance New York City. For years, the mayor has described Ms. McCray as his closest adviser. She is deeply involved in hiring decisions for senior roles at City Hall, and her name has sometimes appeared alongside the mayor's in official news releases announcing senior hires.</Para><Para>Earlier this month, Mr. de Blasio said he believed Ms. McCray should be paid for her work, something the city's ethics laws prohibit. Later, Ms. McCray said she didn't agree with the mayor. "I asked him today when he called me, like, 'Why did you say that?' " she told reporters when asked about the mayor's remarks. "Yes I'm one of his advisers. But sometimes husbands say things."</Para><Para>A slight majority of voters, 46%, said Ms. McCray should be paid for her work on behalf of the city, compared with 45% who didn't. Among white voters, 35% said she should be paid, compared with 49% of Hispanic voters and 61% of black voters.</Para><Para>Write to Mara Gay at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:mara.gay@wsj.com">mara.gay@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Mara Gay </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chirlane-mccrays-job-approval-higher-among-new-yorks-black-voters-1522270916" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

